{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b0908747-fd77-4153-8f46-08caa5d1a784","content":"CLR activation logs diagnose **runtime loading/selection issues** (e.g., wrong CLR version picked, runtime not found, unexpected Feature-on-Demand dialogs). They won't help with a `NullReferenceException`, which is an application-level bug that occurs *after* the runtime has already loaded successfully.\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException, try these instead:**\n\n1. **Enable first-chance exception logging** — run with a debugger attached or use `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1`\n2. **Check the stack trace** — it will point to the exact line where a null reference is dereferenced\n3. **Collect a crash dump** — use `dotnet-dump collect` or configure `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1`\n\nIf you can share the **stack trace** or **crash dump**, I can help pinpoint the null reference. Or if you believe the issue truly is that the **wrong CLR version is loading** (and that's causing the crash), I can invoke the CLR activation debugging skill — just let me know!","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e08c80b-f8de-441e-aa4d-c6f948aa0cc5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\" This seems relevant to the user's request about analyzing CLR activation logs.\n\nLet me invoke this skill.","outputTokens":374},"id":"5c4374e8-7119-4726-be3e-7d08f5c13277","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:15:14.002Z","parentId":"d74d232b-7b84-481a-8acc-143a08fc8d8d"}
